So Revolution Makeup has been going down in quality considerably due to corporation politics (they're flooding the market). I personally hadn't noticed because the occasional eyeshadow palette I own is great. But newer products get bad reviews and it's no wonder with the quantity they spit out - and the low prices. Sad. I loved being able to afford sexy stuff from the drugstore that actually had nice quality.
(Besides that there's the issue of Revolution not only duping large corp stuff but also smaller indie brands without even bothering to hide the fact.)

Even sadder: Revolution bought out BH Cosmetics and it's very likely they'll kill the quality of the brand as well. I was so happy to have discovered BH, because again: great quality, affordable. (Still recommend the Take Me to Brazil palette, if you're looking for a large rainbow variety.)

Possible alternative: the inhouse products from Beauty Bay. I think they are improving a lot? First I didn't think much of them because one: they are obviously dupe. And two: they are as cheap as no-name stuff on Amazon. The reviews on their own website weren't giving much either. But lately I've been seeing more and more beauty creators use especially eyeshadow palettes from BB. And it looks good. Now I got a good review from a friend as well, so I'm defs down to trying.

I'm rapidly approaching 4k toots and horrifyingly, I also see 1k followers on what probably is far closer than the horizon :zerotwo_yikes:

As much as I've written sheet music more consistently in the last month than I have in the rest of my life, and had more non-solo playtime than I have in since my time performing as part of the debut performance series of Bad World a year or two ago (or maybe the other performance series I had at the other theatre (gods, names elude me as always)), I feel like I haven't actually *posted* anything that's really music-related in at least a week or two :psyduck_sweat:‚Äã

What the heck am I going to do to celebrate 1k followers? Come to think of it, who the heck are you all? Like, 1000 people is...a ton. I don't feel it when it's views on a video or something, but to imagine that many real, breathing people seeing my often wildly non-music-related, ranty, often rather crude posts (including lewd stuff) is honestly breathtaking, and confusing, and so, so many other emotions that I can't even identify right now, let alone process :zerotwo_oh:

Whatever you follow me for, my wish is always that I leave your life just a little better than it was when you met me :espeon_love:‚Äã

#Musician #MusicianLife #Violinist #TaviMeta #Fedi #Musings

p.s. I'm oddly proud of the fact that I've managed to keep my following count somewhere in the ballpark of my followers count. I don't want to just come, broadcast, and leave. I want to and really, truly enjoy being part of the various communities here. Even in strife, even from people I don't necessarily fully agree with, I've had wonderful compliments sent my way that I wouldn't have dreamed of receiving. Some even that I feel like I've yet to earn but want to live up to.

I've been able to expand my horizons, my knowledge, my understanding of people and the world we inhabit in so many unforeseen and fun ways. That's not something I can say of any other official account I hold under my stage name, and really, even under my off-stage name, come to think of it :leafeon_giggle:‚Äã

To all the people that make this place wonderful, interesting, and worth coming back to day after day, thank you from the core of my heart :espeon_love:‚Äã :zerotwo_hearts:‚Äã

Replayed Dragonfall recently and it's the bleakest cyberpunk I've seen. Nothing you care about will survive the epilogue except your found family.

In the story, you live in a funny trade district of anarchist Berlin. It's awesome. You can donate for a homeless shelter, make a trade deal with another district, just do a lot of good for the neighbourhood while messing with the corporations.

Then the Bad Guys come and torch the place while you're out. Some of the familiar faces die, more if you didn't bother with the shelter and everything. Hopefully, they'll rebuild.

Then a dragon comes in and destroys the city anyway. Oh, you stopped that threat? Enjoy your happy ending, but the epilogue is "next year, three corporations merged their forces and got rid of the anarchist city".

There's nothing you can do about the epilogue except doom the whole world instead.

The mods and admins on tech.lgbt have gone to great lengths to try to deescalate this dumb drama, only for the people involved in mastodon.art and the bad space to double down and keep destroying thousands of connections between people.

All because of some massive bad faith interpretation of events, which were originally caused by their own fuck up of adding tons of trans instances on a block list.

Don't use block lists, unless they have a very clear, audited, democratic process.

This bad space thing is literally just a few people trying to kick entire communities off mastodon over personal fights. There is 0 oversight and accountability on how this thing works.

The people on mastodon.art won't even see this but yeah, don't stay on an instance that is cutting you out from other completely innocent instances.

I've been on this instance for a while and have never seen toxic behaviour from our mods, and they always take care of bad people.

I really need to make it clear that there's a big difference between a few things:

2) Admins blocking entire instances: technically they do what they want to, but this should really only be done when there's a big problem and no choice. You really don't want thousands of people to lose their social connections just because you once had a fight with a mod

3) Admins doing that but also creating a global blocklist and adding instances to it, and trying to make it a thing that other instances use: Okay so at this point you're basically saying the random queer people on tech.lgbt are so bad that they need to be universally blocked?

Do you realise that people on this instance are just queer people chilling?

You can't brand an entire queer community like that. mastodon.art people are abusing their powers and use the size of their instances to bully people into leaving smaller ones.

- manual pause/step/reset
- run once / continuous
- cascade to a second unit
- glide (portamento), with both manual control and CV (linear only)

This trademark wheeze is the latest desperate tactic to be deployed by the ruling class in the face of a surging labor movement with broad public support. #Starbucks - one of the world's most notorious unionbusters - is doing the same thing to its union, #StarbucksWorkersUnited:

https://seattle.eater.com/23923490/starbucks-workers-united-union-lawsuits-copyright-trademark-israel-hamas-palestine-social-media

These moves are wildly out of step with the current of public opinion, which has swung hard for union rights in a manner not seen in generations.

The outpourings of public support for striking entertainment industry workers were handwaved away as exceptions driven by the public's love of actors and writers. But that doesn't explain the strong, ongoing support for the #UAW in their strike against all of the Big Three automakers:

https://pro.morningconsult.com/instant-intel/uaw-strike-public-opinion-october-2023

Bosses have always tried to smash worker power by dividing workers - by race, gender, or "skill" - but workers are workers and solidarity is the source of worker power.

Creative workers are part of a class of workers who suffer from #VocationalAwe, the sense that because your job is satisfying and/or worthy, you don't deserve to get paid for it:

https://www.inthelibrarywiththeleadpipe.org/2018/vocational-awe/

(Think of joke about the dad who finds his runaway son at the circus shoveling elephant shit: "Son, come home!" "What, and quit show-biz?")

7/

Creative workers have long been encouraged to see themselves as "independent businesspeople" - LLCs with MFAs - and this mind-zap is augmented with our bosses' repeated insistence that the unions are for big burly blue-collar workers, not ethereal dreamers and pencil-pushers. Our bosses tell this story because it discourages us from forming unions and demanding fair pay and good working conditions (obviously).

Ooof, I'll go to sleep now.

I actually finished my "Passwordless login", or rather: the new auth-server for netfiles, which *includes* passwordless login aka Passkey (including Yubikey, etc. support). It works, it is great, and it introduced a significantly higher level of security.

Now, the login process has a significantly better UX as well as significantly higher level of security for the apps and the whole system.

It took me two weeks to come up with the security concept, the plan and the implementation and I am kind of proud. There are some people who, of course, always find a hair in the container full of soup (someone's Windows password manager auto-fills the fields, which is not my fault atm, but hey, I can still fix that shit) and that is really annoying. I mean, this shit is really complex and the whole workflow has to be perfect to support oAuth2-style authentication for the future and what do I get: "But, but, I can't use passwordless because my password manager automatically fills in these fields" (go f*** yourself).

Also, it now needs to be supported by the existing netfiles website as well as the new one we're building. I should be able to integrate it into the new one within a day or so (not really very complicated there), but I have no idea how to integrate the new auth-server in the existing website. I mean, the existing code doesn't even know what a REST-API is (which it has to use only *once* to retrieve the auth-token created and prepared for it and left on the server), so, yeah, there is a bit of work to be done there.

Anyways, I did as promised and delivered in Oct 2023 the auth-server with Passkey-support for macOS/iOS, Windows and Linux (Safari, Chrome, Edge, and all Chromium-based browsers). We still have to see if it also works with Firefox, but it should as Firefox also supports Webauthn.

Where was I? Oh, yeah, good night...

Good night (short and sweet)*. Sleep well all.

*: Maybe I'll re-start my customary "Good night" sometime soon, but atm I don't really feel that I have any spoons left...

Y'know what's really damningly simple to observe?

Used to be getting trans care, HRT or surgery, required a mental diagnosis. In duplicate even! An external label of wrongness. A branding. A painted target.

Now, even just in the past year or so since new guidelines released, it's no longer an external criteria. We're allowed to simply declare and receive.

But there are still some fuckers out there who assume that when we declare ourselves and receive care these days that we've still, as before, receiving some label of wrongness. The branding. The painted target. Like we 'ask' for those things now the same way we would 'ask' for it before.

The things that were forced on us are now the things assumed of us.
